  "opinion": "As a woman in my sixties who’s spent most of her life in Naples, I’ve seen how science and its progress often feel distant from the everyday lives of people like me. The gender gap in science isn’t just about fewer women in labs or universities—it’s about how the very idea of science seems to belong only to those with certain backgrounds, educations, and even the right kind of confidence. My parents both had college degrees, but they were from a different generation when science was still seen as a male-dominated field. I remember my mother telling me how she’d often hear her male colleagues say things like, 'Science isn’t for girls,' even when she was teaching in schools. Today, I still worry that the same attitudes linger, especially for women from working-class backgrounds or those who didn’t go to college. The gap isn’t just numbers—it’s about who gets to feel they belong in these spaces. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big, top-down policies that ignore the real struggles of people like me who work full-time, have family responsibilities, and don’t have the luxury of time to navigate complex systems. Instead, we need to start small: in my own community, in my hair salon, I’ve seen how talking openly about science in simple terms—like explaining how vaccines work or why the ocean matters—can spark interest in young girls. It’s not about changing the system overnight, but about creating spaces where everyone feels they can contribute, no matter their background. I believe the answer lies in listening more, sharing stories that feel personal and relatable, and making sure science isn’t seen as something that only the privileged few can understand or participate in.",
